	Great for conventioneers but leisure travelers are overlooked.	We traveled to San Francisco to get married and chose the Intercontinental based on it's star rating, reviews from other travelers and location. The rooms were spacious, room service food was delicious and the location of the hotel is very convenient for getting to/from SFO and various points of interest in the city. There were some aspects of our stay that I think will be useful to other travelers considering this hotel:1. The hotel places a $200 HOLD on funds from your credit card or debit card for EACH DAY of stay. Those funds are not available to you during this period of time. At the end of your stay, your actual expenses are then totaled and any remaining balance from the frozen funds are released back to your card. This is not spelled out on the hotel's website or third-party reservation websites and posed a problem for us, as we were not prepared to lose $200 of spending money each day. This information should be made available to guests prior to their arrival. The hotel desk clerk informed us that this information was not relayed to us by Expedia (whom we used to book our stay), but I checked Intercontinental's website and could not find this information there, either. If it is there, it should be more prominent. They also could have mentioned this when I called to confirm our reservation the day before our arrival. Let me be clear: I don't have a problem with the policy of holding funds, but there is no reason why guests should be surprised at check-in, when they can be informed beforehand, which would allow guests to plan their travel budget/spending accordingly.2. The front desk service is mediocre. Not very friendly (although not rude) and I was surprised that no one ever even asked us why we were in SF. Given that this is a convention hotel, perhaps they just assumed we were business travelers. Not the case. It would have been nice to be asked. Also, we were not wished an enjoyable stay, nor were we asked if we were satisfied at the end of our stay..minor points, but when it comes to service, the little things count.3. The bar and restaurant are woefully inadequate to handle all of the conventioneers and other guests (i.e. US). After getting married and having our photos taken in and around the city, we returned for some celebratory champagne..We found seats in the very-crowded lounge area, but the waitress that was taking orders ignored us. We fought our way up to the bar and eventually got some attention.4. And perhaps the most annoying part of our stay..the comfort of our room. Our room faced east and when the sun rose each morning, the room became hot. Not just warm. HOT. We had the thermostat adjusted to the lowest possible setting and the fan turned on &quot;high,&quot; yet we still roasted the morning of our wedding as we showered and dressed. We were told the hotel was booked to capacity, so no other rooms were available. Some things cannot be controlled or fixed, but this was still disappointing. It didn't ruin our day, but a pickier bride and groom-to-be might throw a fit.Finally, the parking is quite expensive. We were told that we would be charged $43 per day for parking at the hotel. It was $53 on check-out. Luckily, we found a garage DIRECTLY behind the hotel (and probably the one they use for guests' cars) that charged $32/day. While this may all sound very negative, we were not UNhappy with the hotel. But we won't choose it again. Overall, I would say it's great for conventioneers, and mediocre for people traveling for leisure/special events.NOTE: We did not tell the hotel we were getting married. We did not expect or want preferential treatment. The criticisms noted above have to do with basic service and are not based on an expectation of special treatment. Every guest is entitled to comfort, care and a clear understanding of the cost of their stay.	
	Great time!	We loved the room, the restaurant, the spa, and the surrounding area for sightseeing and restaurants. We had a great time and I'd go there again.	
	Shiny and bright hotel let down by bad service	I agree with those recent reviewers who have identified service problems at this hotel. At best, I would say that it is inconsistent. The bell desk, valet parking, housekeeping, and restaurant staff were all very pleasant and helpful. The front desk staff, however, were largely unhelpful, slow, and in at least one instance, unprofessional.Check in took longer than usual, as the person checking us in had to consult with her supervisor on multiple occasions to ask what seemed to be fairly routine questions. We were using a &quot;buy one, get one weekend night free&quot; certificate (from IC's Ambassador program), and the supervisor actually complained out loud about how customers with these certificates never give the hotel any advance notice about using them. She actually voiced this complaint to our faces. I thought that was highly unprofessional, especially since that is how the &quot;buy one, get one&quot; program is supposed to work: customers are not asked to provide advance notice about using the certificates. In the end, even though we had originally booked a room rate that was supposed to include breakfast, the supervisor informed us that we would not be getting breakfast on the second day because we were using the free certificate. Although I can understand the logic behind this policy, the information was conveyed to us in a rather unpleasant and haughty manner by the supervisor, which left a bad taste in my mouth.Check out also took longer than usual. Even though there were only three people in line, it ended up taking nearly 15 minutes for the front desk staff (two different people from the check-in pair) to get to us. Without making eye contact, the front-desk agent mumbled an apology about the wait. Not a big deal, but another illustration of the amateurish level of service -- and probable lack of adequate training -- in some of the front-desk staff.The hotel itself is quite shiny and bright. The rooms, as others have mentioned, were spotless and relatively spacious, with nice views over the city. The bathrooms are large, with a separate shower and tub. The location is very convenient to Union Square and the Moscone Convention Center, although the tradeoff is that you are farther away from the more classically &quot;San Franciscan&quot; neighborhoods such as Nob Hill, North Beach, and Russian Hill. (For a first-time visitor to the city, I would recommend one of the Fisherman's Wharf or Nob Hill hotels over this location, but for a repeat visitor, this location is just fine.) The breakfast buffet in the main restaurant is excellent, with a well-prepared array of dishes. The gym is also well-equipped and spacious.Notwithstanding the solid &quot;hard product,&quot; the bad service from the front-desk staff left me with less than warm feelings for the hotel as a whole, and it will make think twice about booking another stay here.	
	look out for their package deals	Was originally going to try and book this hotel using hotwire a couple of months from out planned stay as I was certain this was the hotel that hotwire was going to allocate. Decided to wait closer to our arrival date and see what special were available. Glad we did wait as they had a deal - Escape to San Francisco Package Includes accomodations for two, breakfast for two, complimentary parking, and two cable car tickets Based Upon Availability for maybe an extra $40 a night (not too sure on this)The package deal made the stay great value, we were looking at anywhere from $30+ a day for carparking for our hire car so this closed the deal.Not going to rave too much about the hotel room, except to say that we had an excellent stay.We enjoyed the complimentary breakfasts every morning, they were great full buffet and filling up on their breakfast meant we could often skip lunch as we would rather be sight seeing than eating out somewhere. The staff at breakfast were very polite and they really great to talk to for advice (ask a local). One night on returning late to the hotel (10pm) we had skipped dinner due to our Alcatraz tour and were starving for food. Unfortunately the restaurant was about to close so we couldn't dine there but they did let us order the full restaurant menu and eat it in the bar area. This suited us perfectly as we weren't really suitably dressed for the restaurant and really wanted something to eat as quick as possible so we could return to our room. The food we were served was fantastic and was washed down with a couple of local beers from the bar.We were looking to stay at the Westin St Francis but was very happy with the deal we got here, the WSF had no specials on at the time of our stay and was over twice the price we paid here.Good spot for shopping, which was one of primary reasons to visit SF. a couple of blocks away from Union Square. We even took the dodgy way back to the hotel one night through the streets north of the hotel after dining out late on night but was all good, just a little seedy with a few drunks out on the streets.Couldn't fault this place, but I will mention that I think it is designed more for business stays than the casual overseas tourists that we were. We were quite often the only people not wearing a suite in the lift elevators.	
