Aug 28 2009 	Great hotel and saving tips for parking and breakfast	We stayed at this hotel for 6 nights and it was absolutely fantastic. It's centrally located a few blocks off Market Street and Powell where the Cable Car Terminal is located. Very close to the hotel you can take public transportation to visit any part of the city, including the BART train to the airport which costs $8.20 and takes 30 minutes to get you there. We purchased the 3-day pass for public transportation and got more than our money's worth. If you’re an active person and enjoy walking, you are within walking distance of Union Square, Chinatown and the main shopping district. We’re in our fifties and had no problem walking to Chinatown from the hotel, but I understand that may not be everyone’s cup of tea since you must walk a little over a mile or so to get there, plus all the walking after you get there. Just take bus #30 or 45 about two or three blocks from the hotel and you’ll be in Chinatown in a few minutes. Tourist lines to ride the cable cars are long, so we rode them a couple of times and then stuck to the buses and trains. You can also hop on the cable car at a stop other than the terminals and not have to wait as long. I'd rather share tips with readers on how to save money, so I'll just tell you that the rooms, lounges, spa and restaurant at this hotel are all excellent. The property is beautiful and pretty new and the service is top notch. The concierge desk staff is friendly and extremely helpful and so is the rest of the staff. During our stay, the world famous FC Barcelona Soccer Club and its multi-millionaire star players were staying there and hundreds of fans were lined up outside day and night, but management, security and the staff made it very comfortable for the guests so the spectacle became fun to watch after all.  If you're driving, forget paying the $50 daily valet parking fee at the hotel and park two short city blocks away around the corner on 5th St and Mission for $28-30 overnight. We walked late at night from this parking lot to the hotel and never felt unsafe. Take usual precautions and use common sense as you would in any major city. We rented a car the last two days of our stay because we were traveling to other places in California and that’s what I recommend if you’re in a similar situation because parking is expensive and you can forget about on-street parking at most places. Besides, you don't really need a car to get around in San Francisco. Save money on breakfast by walking one block past the parking lot to a corner café on 5th St and Jesse (about 3 blocks from the hotel and across the old US Mint House) where you can buy a delicious breakfast for about $7 and they make it for you right then and there when you order it. They also serve fresh fruit juices and many other goodies. Sorry, I can’t remember the name of the place, but is on the corner of 5th St and Jesse after you pass the Pickwick Hotel on the same sidewalk. Across the street and diagonal from this café is another location named Latte Express where you can buy fresh donuts and coffee, but no bacon and eggs or hot dishes. These two little places will save you a bunch of money if you’re a breakfast eater and don’t want to pay $15 to $20 per person for a very similar breakfast at the hotel restaurant. Enjoy!	
Aug 27 2009 	Saphire Beauty	This year, the spotlight on a family vacation was placed on taking the Amtrak Train across the country from Buffalo, New York all the way to Emeryville (San Francisco), California. Over 2,000 miles of riding the rails was an amazing experience, but when the train came to it's final stop in. EMY, we had to organize places to stay; awaiting our impending road trip south along the coastline of California. Please note, these hotels were booked months in advanced, therefore the rates were very reasonable for the hotels which were chosen for this vacation, therefore; can not confirm that these great rates would accompany the walk-in rates.To begin this adventure, we needed to stay in San Francisco, as the train arrived across the bay in Emeryville at about 5:00PM leaving very tired passengers looking to get refreshed after 4 days on the train. Once again, I was put in charge of choosing the accomidations and the room which would be used on this vacation. Among tons of speculation and excitement in my household, I did the quoting for the Intercontinental San Francisco among other hotels. This one, of course, came out on top citing a good location (close to the train station, the in- and out-bound highways), the Intercontinental Brand (being one of luxury and excellence), and the various traveller reviews and photos of the property. The rate was secured, the room was booked. We had some difficulty booking online through the Intercontinental website so a quick call to the provided 1-800 number fixed all that.My sleuthing had discovered that they were offering various rooms at various prices (of course), but one had stuck out from all the rest. The hotel was offering us accomidation for us in a &quot;2 Queen Bedroom Suite&quot;. The room was only supposed to be filled by 2 adult patrons, but with that call to the 1-800 number, they pulled some strings and placed us in the room with 2 adults and 1 child. The room promised wall to ceiling windows, two queen beds (with plush beds, pillows and whatnot), large business desk, oversized bathroom, and much more. Everything that anyone would want in a room, for both personal and business travelers.Now, enough about talking about what the room was supposed to look like, let's get into the experience. What it was really like, well folks... it was absolutely fantastic! Would I go so far as to say that it was my favorite hotel, no. That title still holds true to the Hotel Indigo in Amhurst, New York (for reasons which I will go more in-depth later). The hotel itself. A sparkling glimmer of blue upon the horizon of the smog infested city. The location on Howard Street is the perfect place, just off of the major highway connecting the city to Oakland and the Airport, a very convenient spot. The hotel itself, as you have probably noted from the pictures is bright blue with the tinted floor to ceiling windows. The hotel is 33 stories tall, and impossible to miss from anywhere.Upon arrival, we were greeted with very friendly valet staff and the hotel's porter. They offered to take our luggage and park the rental car in the compound downstairs. Now, this is where I will begin to sway from the positive. Before booking the hotel, the agent warned us that there would be a parking charge, and it would be steep as it was in downtown San Francisco. The porter informed us that the total charge for one night's parking under the hotel would be $49.00 before taxes and fees. Yes, is correct: $49.00 PER NIGHT, PER VEHICLE. It's not like you have any choice as per where to park, but watch out. You may be better to take the limousine service to/from wherever you are going, but please be warned. Also notable, California charges you a PARKING tax. So it worked out that parking was about $58.00. Wow, not a good start.The parking issue was quickly accepted, as we trudged into the lobby at around 6:00 PM that night. As we walked upto the check-in counter, we were waiting for service for about 2 minutes while the desk was busy with another customer. Shortly after that 2 minute time, another member of the desk staff arrived to process our arrival. He welcomed us to the hotel, and provided us with the upsell of the Intercontinental Ambassador club. Now, I wasn't paying, and the $150 may be a bit steep, but once I hit the age of majority, I will probably join up the Ambassador plan. If it helps out with my Prioroty Club account, it'll be done for sure. We were given our keys (the jet black 'Intercontinental' card) and we were sent to the 7th floor. I was a little disappointed with the floor, I would have liked to be higher up, to see more out the windows, but the porter (who followed us up with our bags to our room) described that they place the higher floor rooms for those who are staying for longer periods of time. Though on again I wasn't impressed, it was alright, there was nothing really to look at that late at night.We were lead to our room, bags in tow. The key opened the door, and it was like an aura of blinding light subsided to produce our amazing, beautiful, and most of all awesome 2 Queen Suite. The room was deep (see pictures) featuring a long hallway connecting the door to the bathroom and the bedroom. The room was decorated much like the lobby, with modern looking furniture, a 40' or so TV affixed to the wall, the two plush and white beds, the oversized business desk, the sliding door to reveal the bathroom. WOW! It was all so much, this hotel room was absolutely amazing. Upon entering, I was really able to take a look up close at the features of the room. The TV, an LG 40', the beds with a 2 or 3' feather bed add-on and fluffy comforter, the wall to ceiling windows looking out onto Howard St. It was all amazing!To go a little more in depth to the accomidation, I would like to start with the entry hallway and entryway. Entering into the room featured quite an extensive hallway connecting the doorway to the room. The area was a little dull, but what followed the entryway quickly made up for it. Due to the hotel being so new, they are able to add in many different features which would come with newer buildings. What I am leading upto would be the electronic controls featuring &quot;Do Not Disturb&quot; and &quot;Make Up Room&quot; which both do exactly as they say,but in a way which require no effort on the part of the guest. Great innovation! Also included here was the closet featuring automatic lights (turning on when the door opens and off when the door closes), an in-room safe which they say is large enough to hold a laptop (I don't know about that...), and of course extra pillows and blankets. I, of course, opted to take all the pillows which I could find for myself (6 in total which were available throughout the room (without taking the parent's).Moving into the main room, you are introduced to a vast space of all that is Intercontinental. On the left of our room there was the TV and underneath was a table or dresser featuring the mini-bar and storage dresser (complete with coffee machine using Tassimo technology). On it's reverse side were the two Queen beds. We were very lucky to get the ability to secure this room, they were very large (for a Queen), immensely comfortable (feather bed topping made the bed so soft), and came complete with 5 pillows each. The whole package equaled an unparalled sleeping experience later that evening, I haven't slept that well for a very long time (in a hotel, that is). Beside the beds lied the oversized business desk. The desk featured a very new Nortel phone featuring colour screen describing all of the room features and welcoming us to the room (of course with the name of the guests)!Last but not least, the bathroom. Oh the bathroom! Featuring your standard fixings (as required by law xD), they brought the bar up a notch. The shower, spacing the entire width of the room, glassed in with an oversized glass door and specialty shower head was truely a delight to use after using a cramped shower/toilet combination on the Amtrak train over the past 4 days! Settings set to: &quot;Rain&quot;, &quot;Massage&quot;, and &quot;Pulse&quot; were great to get back to that crisp and clean feeling I had come to miss over the past few days. The bathroom also featured a completely separate bathtub on the opposite side of the room. The ammenities were first class, imported from the Czech Republic by some company. As usual, they were the usual fixings, but were oh so good!Everything was great, the night's sleep was great in the most comfortable bed on earth and made the night pass by very quickly. Unfortunately, the hotel stay had to come to an end, so it was time to check-out and head down to the next stop on our journey this evening. The next morning, and early rise was accompanied by the bill collection. The room was the same great rate as was advertised, the only kicker was the parking. $49.00, plus the California State &quot;Parking Tax&quot;, and some other stupid charge which brought it up to the high 50's. Otherwise, there weren't really any other surprises, leaving us happy campers!My final statement, falling behind the Hotel Indigo in Amhurst, New York; the Intercontinental San Francisco takes 2nd place on my list of favorite accomidations. The hotel is stunning, brand new, and is full of everything you would ever want and need. If you get a chance to stay in SF, you MUST stay here, you won't be disappointed!All this raving about the place and it only gets 2nd place, you ask? Well, San Francisco stacks up as the city I will NEVER visit again. The location is near Union Sq. which is also full of people panhandling, bothering you every few seconds, and then occastionally trying to steal your wallet and belongings (lovely experience, really... chasing off some idiot nearly reaching into my pocket.) SF was just not a good place to be, if you don't have to go, don't. If you have small children, stay even farther away. You wouldn't want to scare them away from the Big City atmosphere. Try somewhere else like Chicago, there you will give them a more warm approach to the big city!I hope this review helped you choose your accomidations!	
