Jul 16 2009 	New and modern but otherwise a typical 4/5-star chain hotel	I've stayed at the Intercontinental twice this year, in January and June. For both stays, I was there for only a few days.Rooms: Since this is a new hotel, the rooms are well-appointed and large. The room had a very large flat-screen television, desk, and large king bed. The rooms have large windows (floor to ceiling), but there really isn't much to look at directly by the hotel. Perhaps a room on a higher floor would be worth seeking out if you want views of the city.Service and Amenities: The hotel staff was friendly and polite. I didn't make much use of the staff, but my interactions with them were pleasant. One glaring annoyance is that there is not free internet in the hotel. I realize other chains often charge as well, but this hotel doesn't even offer free internet in the lobby. There is a Starbuck's around the corner you can use for WiFi. Location: The location is fine, just a few blocks from Market and right next to Yerba Buena Gardens, and several blocks from Union Square. The neighborhood is safe considering it's San Francisco. I did walk alone at night, but not everyone would feel comfortable doing so. If I weren't familiar with the neighborhood, I would hesitate to stray too far from the hotel.Value: Both times I booked through Hotwire, so I did not make a deliberate choice to stay here. Based on prices quoted on the web site, Expedia, etc., this hotel is overpriced. If you really want to stay in Union Square, then you will end up paying for it, but even so, there are less expensive hotels of similar quality in the area. I usually try to avoid this area of town because it is packed with shopping tourists, but for both of these trips, it was really convenient. Also, when booking on Hotwire, I try to stick with neighborhoods I know.P.S.Restaurant: I was very excited to try the restaurant, since the chef was recently recognized as best new chef in Esquire, but I was really disappointed. The service was the highlight. Food and wine were served promptly by informed waitstaff. The decor in the restaurant is pretty cheesy (an attempt at chic 1970s retro, perhaps?) I had the tasting menu for $34, so I didn't expect a big meal. I would expect that a seasonal tasting menu would not include things like New Zealand scallops and out-of-season strawberries (in June), especially in San Francisco. It was fine, but even for $34, it really wasn't enough food to be considered even a light lunch. It wasn't so bad that I wouldn't give it another shot, but there are just too many good restaurants in San Francisco.	
