Jan 11 2009 	Comfortable Hotel with excellent service	Stayed six nights at the Intercontinental SF. Upon arrival were upgraded to a one bed suite on the 32nd floor as part of our Ambassador Priority club package. Great room with separate sitting room and one and a half bathrooms, very handy when one of you cannot adjust to time difference and the other is still asleep!! Great views of the city and - when the fog cleared on the third day- a glimpse of the golden gate bridge and the bay.Our suite was spotlessly clean, everything worked fine and it had the most comfortable bed and a wonderful bathroom complete with TV! There was ample storage space with two closets and heaps of drawers. The one cup coffee maker meant having to run it twice to make coffee for two but no big deal. The room decor was distinctly 'Intercontinental' which can verge on the conservative 'grey-beige' but the room layout and views make up for this. The decor in public areas is more exciting.At first we thought the hotel was a little out of the way but after a couple of days we felt that the location was pretty good - very close to the streetcars on Market and the cable cars on Powell. Close to Union Square and of course the Westfield shopping centre. For us, tourists on our first trip to San Francisco, the location turned out to be ideal. The two other advantages of the location are that the area is fairly flat around the hotel if you are not used to the steep hills and you have the great views from the hotel as there are no tall buildings close by.Easy walk from hotel to Museum of Modern Art, the excellent contemporary Jewish museum and Yerba Buena gardens. Streetcars on Market run you to Fishermans wharf/Castro for $1.50.Had breakfast twice at the hotel $25 for the buffet was pretty good with endless coffee and OJ and my partner enjoyed the spa with fairly reasonably priced treatments.All in all a very well run hotel, good location for tourists and great views, excellent service from reception, housekeeping, concierge and guest relations.	
Jan 10 2009 	Nice Hotel with "Modern Problems"	This Intercontinental is less than a year old, and is what you'd expect in a new, five-star hotel in a major city. It does have a range of &quot;modern hotel problems&quot;, however.I was upgraded to a nice, high-floor corner room due to my Ambassador Club status. Hotel was pretty empty, despite a major convention at Moscone Center (a block away). Rooms are tastefully appointed, clean and comfortable. A/C system is particularly good, very quiet. However, when I first checked in, I was warned that a &quot;maintenance issue&quot; would require the hotel electricity to be turned off for an hour that afternoon. Fair enough. But during the late night hours, while I was working (phone and internet), the power again went out along with all communications - AND THE ELEVATORS. No warning at all. This pattern of electrical service continued for the next day as well. Apparently still-unresolved construction issues. The phones go down because of a too-small UPS system specified. My other &quot;modern hotel&quot; pet peeve is the showers. Part of luxury hotel life is a good, powerful hot shower. Instead this hotel has barely enough water pressure to get wet. If this is due to some kind of &quot;green initiative&quot;, I object. If this is just due to bad water-saving shower heads, it should be fixed. Midline management was dismissive of the concerns I raised. I was able to finally raise the hotel manager with a call to IC head office about the electrical/communication issues. Management shouldn't be hiding from the customers.One other note for potential visitors - much of SFO including the area adjacent to this hotel has become extremely street unsafe, even during the daytime. Factor in cab fares if you're planning on doing sightseeing.	
