Jan 5 2009 	Great place for our anniversary	I stayed here in early January as a staycation for my five year anniversary. My boyfriend and I booked it on hotwire for $140 including all taxes ($119 before taxes). It was listed as Union Square East, which is not really accurate since it's in SOMA, but it was still in an area that was nice enough. We live here so the homeless don't surprise us, but if you're coming from a non-urban area anywhere in SF is going to have that problem. If it had been located one block south or west it would not be in a good location, but it was right inside what we consider to be the border of the upscale area downtown.We got there early in the day and left our bags with the bellhop. I lost my ticket when we came back, but he was able to retrieve them with my driver's license, which was a relief. Everyone was so polite we were sort of taken aback. Check in took only a few minutes, and we explained why we were there when asked. We got booked into a queen size room on the 14th floor (1405 I belive). When we got to the room I was very disappointed with the size. It couldn't have fit a king size bed had someone put it in there. The bathroom was even more disappointing as it didn't have a bathtub and I really wanted to soak my feet after walking around all day. I went downstairs and asked if it would be possible to be moved to a room with a bathtub. His response was &quot;It's your anniversary, of course you can!&quot; which was a relief. We got moved to the 9th floor to a king size room. It was about twice the size and had a separate shower and bath. That changed it from a 2-3 star to a five star experience. We took advantage of the jacuzzi and swimming pool twice in less than 24 hours. Both were such great temperatures and the jacuzzi was big enough that even when an entire family came in there was plenty of room. The TV was huge and we almost rented a movie but decided against it. Most cost between 10-14 dollars, and include those that are in between theatre and DVD. Bed was a little soft for my taste, but my boyfriend loved it. The blankets were plush and wonderful. This was a perfect escape for one night, and if I could get this price again I would stay there in an instant.	
Jan 3 2009 	A flawless stay	Just back from a great stay at the InterContinental in San Francisco, one of the best and most hassle-free hotel stays I've had in a long time. This brand-new hotel is convenient, comfortable, and peaceful, with big rooms and smooth, unobtrusive service. Everything just works really well here. Highly recommended.The hotel occupies a soaring blue-glass tower in the trendy South of Market (SOMA) neighborhood; it's two blocks south of Market Street, the main downtown thoroughfare, and maybe a 10-minute walk from Union Square. The decor is sleek and modern, but not too aggressively cool; the lobby is relatively low-key, with a bar and restaurant, giving the comfortable feel of a smaller hotel even though the hotel is quite large.My room, on the 17th floor, was impressively spacious, well-appointed, and tricked out with the latest gadgets, from the motion-sensor light in the entry to the huge high-def flat-screen TV. But unlike a lot of new hotels, the space had been designed very intelligently; the wall unit had ample room for desk space and a long counter, and a window seat and a long ledge in the bathroom gave the sense of additional space to spread out. The bed was very comfortable, with super-soft pillows. The bathroom was also big, with a glassed-in shower. I had decent views from the very big windows toward Union Square and the Civic Center.If you're sensitive to noise, you'll like this: the hotel is impressively quiet. Entering your room is like stepping into a cocoon of silence. There's almost no street noise. I was returning to my room one evening and could hear my neighbor talking very loudly on his phone through his door; but once I entered my room I couldn't hear a thing.Service was smooth and efficient but unobtrusive. There was always someone standing in the lobby to greet you. Wake-up calls were delivered on time, and room service arrived promptly. Housekeeping kept the room very clean.A bonus: the hotel's food is excellent. I didn't eat in the restaurant, Luce, but I had a fantastic Luce burger at the bar (San Francisco has some odd ideas about how to season french fries, but they were still good), and a delicious chicken and eggplant panini from room service. The only possible drawback to the hotel is the location; it's a little off the beaten path, and the block it's on is a little desolate. However, it is right next to the Moscone Center and just a block or two away from the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, Yerba Buena Gardens, and Metreon, and it's just two blocks south of the Powell Street BART/Muni station. (Hint: If you're coming here from SFO and traveling light, don't take a taxi, which will cost a fortune and take forever; BART will zip you straight from the airport to Powell Street in about 30 minutes for just over $5.) There's also a stiff charge ($15/day) for in-room Internet access, but that's true of almost all luxury hotels; at least the network was reasonably fast.Overall, this is a fantastic place to stay, especially for the business traveler or the seasoned tourist who wants to be a little bit away from the hustle and bustle.	
