Aug 25 2008	Loved this hotel!	This is one beautful glass towering hotel. I was amazed at how well the hotel spaces were designed and the amount of thought that was put into the selection of furniture, wall paper, art, colors, tiles, and granite and fixtures in the bathrooms. I probably would define the spaces as comtemporary with emphasis on clean lines, comfortable textures, warm but neutral tones. The hotel is situated about three blocks south of Union Square and I appreciated it’s location. The area is clean, spacious, safe, and without the crowds and noise of Union Square. It only added to that laid back San Franciscan attitude. The walk is short and easily managed with luggage from the Powell BART station. Bart is faster and way cheaper ($5.35) than a cab from the airport. It is a clean, efficient, comfortable travel mode. I think one of the problems with the hotel is that they have so many codes including different rooms and packages that even the staff gets a bit confused. I had booked a 400 square foot room with two queen beds in the corner on a lower floor, like 7 to 11 for $229 including breakfast. Well, this doesn’t exist. These corner rooms (two walls of windows) only have one bed We were given a 400 sq. foot room with two queen beds that oddly was a bit claustrophobic but not in a corner. When I spoke with Janet, the manager, she could not bend over backwards enough to rectify the situation. We were upgraded to the 28th floor with bay view, slightly smaller room (you would never know it) 360 sq. feet with 2 double beds. It was amazing. She took us around to view several rooms AND gave us vouchers for drinks at the bar. The bay view during the day was lovely but even better at night with the lights of the city. Looking at the city view from the hallway, it was pretty spectacular too, especially at night. The room had an ironing board, iron, hairdryer, umbrella, extra pillows, and blanket. The pillows on the bed were a bit flat but one call and we had five pillows on each bed! Nice fat ones too. Toiletries are included as well as a magnifying mirror. The bathroom is large, spacious and did have a tub. The first room we had been given did not have a tub but a beautiful shower area instead. The door to the bathroom was a large frosted glass sliding door, very cool. The room had a thermostat for temperature control, and an ihome radio-alarm clock with ipod dock. There was a larger than life flat screen TV. Little buttons on the lamps (on-off control) are lighted at night and the far bed nearer the window has a button on the wall to light up the entry way. We heard no noise from the hall or other rooms. Occasionally at night we heard a siren from an emergency vehicle. There are two phones in the room, one wireless. The concierge was very helpful and offered many options to all of our inquires. Hotel personnel were really nice. And check out was pleasant, fast, and efficient.There is a very pretty lap pool and jacuzzi located on the 6th floor (available to alll) as well as a club room for those that booked a club room floor. You can also purchase club room access for 80 dollars a day with any other room which includes breakfast, afternoon tea, drinks and dessert.Buffet breakfast is amazing, Try to get it included in your rate otherwise, 27 dollars a person. I did notice that there was a coffee urn set up on the bar just before the restaurant area for coffee with take away cups in the morning. And there is a Starbucks on your way to Union Square.Westfield Mall is on your way to Union Square also. They have a food court, eh, and a nice food market, Bristol Farms, in the lower level which offers hot and cold take away meals. The fourth floor of the mall has several good restaurants including Zazil, a innovative mexican restaurant with fabulous Margaritas. Bottom line, I am glad I booked the InterContinental and would stay there again without question.	
